The losers remain challengers
HARARE: Before the presidential elections this month, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they received terror.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by Robert Mugabe's party, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-sponsored terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is the work of crooked elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
As a result of intimidation and violence, my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in many areas, particularly in rural regions.
Furthermore, my opponent's government, President Mugabe's, effectively disempowered hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, especially in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations in total, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone without being able to cast their ballots.
I continue to question the legitimacy of the election results, because Mugabe's militia prevented the MDC from deploying election observers in 52% of rural polling stations.
Towards the end of the voting, our party lacked observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were controlled solely by ZANU supporters.
In our preliminary investigations, a pattern has already emerged: in these polling stations, the majority of votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the results of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is in their eyes illegitimate.
The people of Zimbabwe have been deprived of their right to elect a president of their choice freely and democratically.
The struggle over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are in short supply, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and deserve to have this recognized.
Perhaps it is not too late for this.
I write this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still ignores the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as their loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
Perhaps the government will arrest me.
I was also arrested for treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the people's will to reclaim their rights and power.
It is up to us to carry out a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overwhelm us.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be prepared to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to finish what we have started together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who would not be intimidated.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very rocky path together to achieve democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely had to endure such violence and yet have managed to preserve kindness and enthusiasm.
I can see that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot just leave these elections as they are, but they must also not fall for Mugabe's provocations and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all the obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that in all of Africa, elections are rigged.
In most African countries, irregularities, fraud, and deception in elections seem to be the norm.
In Africa, there is always some crisis because of elections.
It is sad, but the whole continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it is time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not over yet.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I swear not to leave them.
